results.title: A Crop of records
results.brief_description: In 1960, Victoria’s wheat growing record was smashed by a bumper harvest. 95% of the wheat was from varieties bred by the Victorian Department of Agriculture including Pinnacle; Insignia; Beacon; and Olympic. Don Rooney, an agronomist in the Wimmera region talks to Victorian farmer Harry Bouchier about his record harvest. We follow the wheat’s journey from the farm, to the silos and finally being loaded onto cargo ships at the Port of Geelong headed for international destinations.

results.title: Come September
results.brief_description:
Opens with the showgrounds devoid of people, livestock and produce, before contrasting this with the show in full swing.

Includes footage of people wandering around, livestock, produce, rides, food and ‘fun’ being had.

No narration, only location sound and upbeat music. This makes for a sophisticated and enoyable film, where the experiences of the people it captures are the focus.

Nice ‘night’ sequence with fireworks.

Great hand-painted credits that mimic various signs allready up at the showgrounds.

Great film!

results.title: Powerslide for PC
results.material_description: CD-ROM videogame. CD-ROM in CD jewel case with insert and manual
results.brief_description: After an environmental holocaust killed 98% of the world’s population, the survivors above ground turned to modifying and racing the cars left over in the ruins of civilization. In the ruined world of Powerslide, players race through abandoned cities buried in sand, ruins of a dam, abandoned mine shafts, and other desolate landscapes. Perform death-defying jumps and slide through the corners as you eke out each win! This racing sim has full car dynamics, force feedback, and full multiplayer support.

results.title: Autarky
results.brief_description: An exploration of the possibilities that the intergration of digital technology and the natural world can open up for women. Archetypal feminine symbols and themes suggest that resources for female empowerment and self-sufficency are to be found in the layers beneath the social construction of patriarchy

results.creator_credit: Bayram Ocal, Fatma Coskun, Figen Hasimoglu, Huseyin Duman, Ifran Hassan, Kenan Besiroglu, Memet Gunes, Mustafa Yucel, Riza Guclu, Umit Ugur, Yusuf Hazar, ACMI Digital Storytelling and ACMI
results.brief_description: Eleven Turkish migrants, from Cyprus and Turkey, tell of their experiences migrating and making Australia their new home. They tell of the reasons for moving here, the journey to Australia and share their feelings for their family, their community and their adopted country.
